r:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-072-27-0041</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The project examines the characteristics of climate variability and change in the ravine zone of Chambal Valley in India. The ravines occurring in the area are of the most severe type. For monitoring ravine erosion, it is important to understand the type of ravines and their genesis. Ravine formation has significant socioeconomic implications ie shifting of villages and changes in livelihood. This research examines the climatic processes that contribute to the shaping of ravine formation in a region where use of the natural environment is a key component of livelihoods.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The innovative aspect of the Project lies in the combination of optical remote sensing methods with advanced physical and socio-economic modelling in GIS environment. &lt;br />The proposed work and research will be mainly focused on the following issues:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>to understand ravine extension in the study region;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>to understand the effect of climatic factors in ravine formation in the study area;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>to study the socioeconomic implications of ravine formation through the linkages between the physical and socio-economic factors with the combination of Remote Sensing and GIS techniques.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The livelihood implications of ravine formation will be analysed by examining the linkages between land degradation and agriculture, which is the main source of livelihood for a majority of people in this ecologically fragile region.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>6460</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The impact of severe land degradation on rural communities is complex and not as clear cut as one initially anticipated. the reasons for this complexity require further consideration beyond the remit of the current project</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The approach used in the publication arising from this project could be sued as a baseline to develop addition research in this area or in similar geographical regions</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>341DD80D-80B0-435B-B692-3314E30433DF</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>544a3759b72bc9.22847525</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>B0B1BB41-A281-480E-81CC-C0AE66AECCCB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Land degradation and spatial vulnerabilities: a study of inter-village differences in Chambal Valley, India</gtr:ti